You can represent the type as long as you keep track of the literal values inside the `id` properties of the elements of the `people` array.  The easiest way to do that is with a [`const` assertion](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-3-4.html#const-assertions):

    const people = [
        { id: &#39;1&#39; },
        { id: &#39;2&#39; },
        { id: &#39;3&#39; },
    ] as const;
    
Then the type you&#39;re looking for is

    type InitValueType = Record&lt;typeof people[number][&#39;id&#39;], { name: string }&gt;;
    /* type InitValueType = {
        1: {
            name: string;
        };
        2: {
            name: string;
        };
        3: {
            name: string;
        };
    } */

And it&#39;s easy enough to use a [type assertion](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/basic-types.html#type-assertions) to get the output of `reduce()` to be what you want:

    const initialValues = people.reduce((acc, p) =&gt; ({
        ...acc,
        [p.id]: {
            name: &#39;&#39;,
        },
    }), {} as InitValueType);

That type assertion isn&#39;t completely type safe; it doesn&#39;t stop some bad things from happening:

    const badInitialValues = people.reduce((acc, p) =&gt; ({
        ...acc,
        [p.id]: {
            kablam: &#39;&#39;, // what?
        },
    }), {} as InitValueType);

But it might be the best you can reasonably do here, since trying to give a typing for `reduce()` that represents the single callback as representing each link in a chain of types that starts with `{}` and culminates in `InitValueType` would be incredibly messy and unlikely to ultimately buy you more safety.  

Okay, hope that helps; good luck!

